{"source_key":"sha256-ea08d35f42d5530fbe92c80d4f5b27e9","record_index":1001,"record_hash":"sha256:78faf076a200b31109def92fcae6a22044c9db76a31dd51de29886a7bc57b983","timestamp":"2026-05-24T16:15:21.970Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: a397f2\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 1\nOriginal token count: 711\nOutput:\n## Filesystem / Cache Architecture\n\nThe generator needs a real local filesystem. Treat the Git/GitMeta cache as a\nlocal working set, not as durable product data.\n\n## Infrastructure Sketch\n\nProduct v1 should be two services:\n\n```text\nBrowser\n  -> Agent Trail web/API facade\n      - parses /<owner>/<repo>/pull/<number>\n      - resolves public GitHub PR facts\n      - starts or polls generation\n      - renders public projection JSON/page\n\n  -> Agent Trail generator service\n      - Rust HTTP service\n      - fetches public refs/meta/main\n      - owns local Git/GitMeta cache\n      - calls but-agentlog projection API\n      - returns or stores bounded public projection\n\n  -> local persistent volume mounted only by generator\n      - repo cache\n      - GitMeta sqlite state\n      - per-repo locks\n      - optional projection cache/index\n```\n\nPreferred first deployment:\n\n```text\nAgent Trail web/API facade: whatever is simplest for the web app\nAgent Trail generator:      Fly Machine\nGenerator storage:          one Fly Volume mounted at /data\nGenerator image:            Rust binary + git installed\n```\n\nThe web/API facade should treat the generator as an internal service with a\nnarrow contract:\n\n```text\nPOST /generate\n  input: github owner, repo, PR number, PR facts, limits\n  output: ready | pending | metadata_missing | no_matches | weak_matches | error\n\nGET /snapshots/<snapshot-id>\n  output: bounded public projection JSON\n```\n\nThe generator may do request/response generation at first. If cold generation is\ntoo slow, switch to queued jobs without changing the storage model:\n\n```text\nweb/API facade -> enqueue job -> generator worker -> projection store\nweb/API facade -> poll status -> render projection\n```\n\nScaling path:\n\n1. one generator process, one volume, per-repo locks\n2. one generator process plus queue if requests need to return quickly\n3. multiple generator shards by GitHub repository id, each with its own volume\n4. optional object storage for immutable projection JSON and backup exports\n\nAvoid shared writable repository storage across generator instances. If multiple\nworkers exist, route each repository to exactly one owner worker or shard.\n\nRecommended v1 architecture:\n\n```text\nweb/API facade -> generator HTTP API -> one generator process\n                                  -> one mounted persistent volume\n```\n\nDecision after parallel storage research: use **Fly Machine + Fly Volume** for\nthe first production deployment unless there is already a stronger organizational\nreason to choose another platform. It is the lightest path that still gives Git\nand SQLite normal local filesystem behavior.\n\nAcceptable development/spike shortcut:\n\n```text\ngenerator process -> ephemeral local scratch -> projection JSON response/cache\n```\n\nUse that only to prove the projection pipeline and measure cold-generation time.\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T16:15:21.970Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}